There was a county truck, gravel truck like, a big truck.
And there were some guys standing around there arguing and some other guys came from inside arguing and they were shouting back and forth at each other as we pulled up.
And Carroll turned to me and he said, I don't want you to say a word.
You talk funny and I don't want these people to have any trouble with us.
I thought that was pretty instructive.
But the other funny word was, funny way they talk here was again in that first year, I had a close association with the town of Mahea, okay?
One of their sons, are you ready for a long story here?
One of their sons had gone off, he was a homosexual.
He was a scion of a old family, long time family there.
He'd gone off to New York City, got in dramatics, got fairly famous and well to do, came back fairly rich, decided to come back to the old hometown and retire.
And then he decided he wanted to resurrect the old Poco Grounds.
It was the Pure Oil Company, P-O-C-O.
It was on the Confederate Reunion Grounds on Jack's Creek.
And he got hold of me because he had read about this department.
He wanted me to come up and help him design a tourist attraction on Jack's Creek

by taking some of the pure oil storage tanks, huge things, and renovating them inside, air conditioning them, making a stage inside, and recreating the history of the plantation era inside the oil tank, okay?
That was his dream.
So I went up several times.
In fact, he did develop enough support that they cleaned up some of the old,

reunion grounds there on Jack's Creek and and they found some of the bathhouse steps that went down to the creek that the people in their parasols had come and Governor Conley came one night the night I'm speaking of after he'd been at another meeting they had him as head speaker to dedicate this thing during his governorship

he got there late everybody else had finished the barbecue and he pulled in it was after dark the lanterns were on and he sat down and ate barbecue by himself at this whole head table with a hundred people watching him eat not saying a word just i'm going to eat before i talk and it was the strangest thing to me that a person would come in and have the
Courage, I guess, or the sense to just stand there and eat.
But the thing about Mejia was, my wife went up with me that night, and she was trying to read the map.
I'd been there a couple times already with this guy, and so I knew where I was going, but Dot was looking at the map.
And I said, we want to go to Mejia.
We've got to go up through Calvert, her and Calvert, and on up.
And she said, I can't find it.
I can't find it.
I can't find it.
And that was the reason, because she was looking for Mexia, and it's M-E-X-I-A.
In fact, I found when you're up there and talking to those people, it's Mehair.
Mehair.
Not Mehea.
But yeah, that was one of the first times that I saw that there was a different language down here.
I'm getting close to the end of the things I've thought of.
Are there some people that you would like to thank that we haven't mentioned?
Well, you know, I didn't give much credence to Wayne Hall, but certainly he was one that did support me in this whole organization thing at the start of this.
Gosh, I'm sure there's just...
I think Wayne Hall is one of the underappreciated people here that he did more...
He was just a quiet gentleman.
Quiet.
And I've learned that Mr. Rutter on academic matters would listen to him.
And among other things, I've learned that he's the one that thought up the name of this institution as it is now phrased.
Really?
Mr. Rutter, we recommended Texas State University.
Mr. Rutter would not stand that at all.
He didn't want to lose A&M.
And so instead of the Agricultural Mechanical College of Texas or Texas State University, he came up with Texas A&M University.
Without the letters.
Which I think has worked pretty well.
Yeah, excellent.
Others you'd like to...
appreciation josh haskell i'd just have to all right you may think of those later before we edit it uh some proud moments that we haven't mentioned proud personal moments
Never had a proud moment in my life.
Okay.
Then two last things.

Let's make believe that someone walks up to you in the next few days and hands you a check for a million dollars, but it's payable to Texas A&M University, but you've got to decide what is done with it.
Oh, wow.
What would you want?
If you had the capacity to give A&M a big sum of money, what would you want that used for?
A million's not big money anymore now when MIT gets 350 million to study the brain.
I'd really have to think about that, but I suspect it would in some way be leveraged to help students.
because the financial thing has got out of hand so much lately that I don't see how people are paying it.
And so much, it seems to me, that comes to the university comes for personal aggrandizement that's short term.
Do you remember over in the MSC originally when
Who was it, the Scotsman that went down to Mexico and had that beautiful circular rug woven with the A&M logo in the middle of it?
I don't know where that rug is now.
Think about that.
I don't either.
And how many buildings have been named and then the names changed when a bigger gift comes in.
And so many of these things really
don't benefit the students.
How would you want the student, the winners, how would you want the recipients to be selected?
I don't know what, I'm not sure that I would want it to be individual selection or instead some mechanism that would

uh... benefit a larger number i'd really have to think about that i'm not certain that a university like this is well that's just way off the subject what i was going to say was whether there's any sense in trying to maintain universities in this form of a pile of bricks and mortar at a single location when we're entering into a time when
With distance education and computers, we can maybe do a better job without babysitting people for four to six years to come and be at a specific location away from home.
Maybe it serves some social purposes other than education, but I'm not sure this is the best way to do education.
Boy, that's not a way to answer your question about how do you spend a million dollars.
Last question, what feelings do you have for Texas A&M in your heart now, after a third of a century?
That sounds so long.
I'm just really thankful to God that I had the opportunity to come here.
It's been a good life.
I think the university treated me more fairly than I probably deserved.
And it was a great location to rear a family.
And they've become staunch Texans even though neither of them are living in the state right now.
If your machine were off, I'd say I'd like to have a lot closer relation with the,
department than I have currently.
And maybe I will again, but I've backed way off in order not to make it appear confrontational.
And if that means moving out of here for a while, I'm willing to do that.
Dorothy's saying, keep that at all costs.
I said, no, it's not that important.
There's other things that are more important.
But I've gained lifelong friends and colleagues that I treasure from being here that length of time.
I don't think for people in the future they will, well you've even moved around more than I have.
I mean I came here and I've been here ever since and you've gone on and done some great things at other places.
before coming back here, but I think it's going to become more of a rarity for people to stay half a century or a third of a century in one job or one location.
We've taught for years about serial occupations, careers.
I think A&M has changed.
tremendously in that length of time, but I think the school has stayed true to its traditions and its origins in a lot of ways that are going to serve it well in the future.
